results.title: The Many Different Characters of  Grocery Store Employees and Customers (My Grocery List of Observations)
results.description:
After shopping for groceries at the same store for many years, I've noticed the many different types of personalities out there...young and old...who are employees or customers.  Several have impressed me in a positive way while others...well....

I suspect you may agree with one or more listed.

If you don't have the $$ to pay for this word document, here it is below.
Perhaps, one will bring a chuckle to start your day. 

Thank you.

Sincerely,

Esther Monsalve
The Angel Shop


The Many Different Characters of 
Grocery Store Employees and Customers
(My Grocery List of Observations)

1.The “Date-Rate” Cashier – A young and obnoxious cashier bragging (as he's scanning my groceries) about last nights date...and how he easily scored.

2.The “Otta Here Now!” Cashier – A middle-aged employee who grabs and tosses each item through the electronic scanner...as though it's a race to collect your cash and scoot you out asap...throwing your canned goods, milk, eggs, etc. obviously not giving a hoot as to damaging your now purchased food.

3.The “You're Invisible” Cashier – He or she won't dare look, greet or even acknowledge you're there...  “Hello?”

4.The “Let's Move In...Too Friendly” Cashier – He or she is so friendly...talkative...inquires about all the unhealthy, sugary items you're buying...then asks personal questions about your life you wish not to share.  Or, they tell you personal information about themselves...perhaps, wanting advice, therapy?....TMI (too much information)

5.The “Rude/Ignoring” Deli Prep – keeps his head down as he prepares the meat and veggies...responding to no one who asks for assistance.

6.The “Human Scanner/Former Football Player” Assistant Manager – He stands near the front entrance staring at everyone who walks in the store...appearing suspicious that you're going to steal a truck load of cosmetics, steaks, beer and/or cigarette cartons. He's ready to tackle even a 5 year old bubble-gum klepto...resulting in a most uncomfortable walk-in.

7.The “After-Hours/After Partying” Customer -  They stroll in the store dressed in a long, low-cut gown, wearing 5” heels and a hair style that must of cost a fortune...only to purchase sanitary pads, toilet paper and Kao-PePe for their hungover partner peuking in the parking lot.

8.The “Super-Mom” Customer -  There are 6-7 kids at her side (ages ranging: 2 yrs to 11 yrs old)...each whining, yelling, throwing tantrums...and...during all this verbal chaos, mom is calm, cool and collected...appearing not at all stressed.  Her secret?  
(M-e-d-i-c-a-t-i-o-n)  
 
9.The “Abusive Parent(s)” Customer -  Without hesitation, smacks their child(ren) and yells demeaning comments that totally embarrasses the kid to the point of tears and a mental shutdown.

10.The “Over Weight, Sweet-Tooth” Bakers – Always sneaking a bite or two when no one is looking.  Those cream-puffs and croissants can be addictive...you know?

11.The “One Bag Bagger” Employee – It doesn't matter how many groceries purchased, he/she attempts to stuff all items into one paper or plastic bag.  That means, your gallon of milk, laundry detergent, dog food, fruits, veggies, eggs and anything else that fits...will be packed.


Esther Monsalve
The Odddoll Antics

Support Operation Smile

Note: Please use MEMO, an editor writing software, in oder to open this digital file.

results.description:
"You are my Sunshine." Great sign for your loved one or some one who adds sunshine to your day. I love this song and so will the person that gets this sign!

This sign measures approximately 5.5 x 12 inches and is on 3/4 inch thick wood. This creation is shown in Burgundy/Antique White.

Two contrasting colors of paint are applied, the design is laser engraved, a fine hairline is applied to the design which gives an awesome touch. The final touches are completed once it goes through our antiquing process with edges distressed.

Keep in mind when selecting the color options, the first color is the text color, while the second color is the background. See policies for additional questions/clarification on colors.

While we try to get the best wood at the lumber yard, sometimes there will be knots or other slight imperfections in the wood, this is considered adding character to the rustic style of this line of our signs.
